The Macedonian people held a referendum on Sunday to determine a name change to the ‘Republic of North Macedonia’. A move that would resolve a dispute with Greece that had lasted for a decade in which Greece had prevented Macedonia from joining the European Union (EU) and the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
Greece, which has its own territory called Macedonia, insists that the name ‘Macedonia’ represents a claim on its territory and has vetoed Macedonia’s participation in NATO and the EU.
The two governments reached an agreement on a proposed name change in June but the nationalist opposition said the change undermined the ethnic Macedonian identity of the majority Slavic population.
President Gjorge Ivanov said he would not vote in the referendum and the vote cast doubts whether the referendum would achieve the minimum 50 per cent vote required for the referendum to be valid.
The question on the ballot was written: "Do you agree to join NATO and the EU by accepting an agreement with Greece?"
Proponents of the name change include Prime Minister Zoran Zaev saying "Receiving the new name is a price worth paying to join the EU and NATO for Macedonia, one of the countries that emerged after the fall of Yugoslavia.
"I have come today to vote for the future of the country and for young people in Macedonia so that they can live freely under the European Union because that means our lives are safer," said Olivera Georgijevska, 79 in Skopje.
Although illegal, lawmakers said they would comply with the vote's decision to make it final.
The change of name requires a two-thirds majority in parliament.
The country's election commission said there were no reports of non-compliance with the rules as of 1 p.m.
However, voting attendance was 16 per cent compared to 34 per cent in the 2016 parliamentary elections after 66 per cent of registered voters threw away ballot papers.
"I came to vote because of my children. Our place in Europe," said Gjose Tanevski, 62, a voter in the capital Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife and their son Dushko cast ballot papers in Macedonia for the country's name change that will pave the way for Macedonia to join NATO and the EU in Strumica, Macedonia on September 30, 2018.
In front of parliament in Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, was setting up a small stage and placing seats in front of a tent set up by people who boycotted the referendum.
"We want to join NATO and the EU but we want to join it with pride and not in this way," Kavadarkov said.
"We are poor people, but we have dignity.
If they don't want to see us as Macedonians, we can turn to China and Russia and be part of the Euro-Asia integration."
Prime Minister Zaev said the participation in NATO would provide sufficient investment to Macedonia where the unemployment rate is more than 20 per cent.
I believe a large majority will accept because more than 80 per cent of our population voted for the EU and NATO," Zaev said after casting the vote.
He said the ‘yes’ decision was ‘a confirmation of our future.’
A poll was published on Monday by the Macedonia Institute for Policy Studies which said between 30 and 43 percent of voters would participate in the poll - below the required amount.
Another poll, run by Macedonian TV Telma, found that 57 percent of respondents planned to vote on Sunday.
70<0x25> of them said they would vote yes.
