John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scottish private schools maintain a track record of academic excellence, and this has continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding exam results, reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other community endeavors.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, the school, represented by the Scottish Board of Private Schools (SCIS), strives to serve at the best level to their students and parents.
The goal of private schools is to prepare their students to pursue higher education, their chosen career, and their place as global citizens.
As the education sector they can and implement the school's curriculum earlier, we see modern languages continue to be well-known and the subject of choice within the school.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to a person in a language he understands, it will go into his head.
If you speak to him in his mother tongue, it will come into his heart."
This is a strong reminder that we can't just rely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the results of this year's exam, we can see that language is the top subject in the league table with the highest passing rate in private schools.
68<0x25> of students who study a foreign language get a higher A grade.
This data, compiled from 74 SCIS school members, showed 72 percent of students got higher A grades in Mandarin, while 72 percent of them studied German, 69 percent of them learned French and 63 percent of those studying Spanish also got A.
This shows that private schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will no doubt need in the future.
Language now, as a subject of choice, is being held just as much as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curriculum of private schools and elsewhere.
A survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that the reasons employers struggle to meet vacancies, 17 percent attributed to a lack of language skills.
Because of that again and again, language skills become a must to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more prospective job opportunities requiring language, these skills are essential in this globalized world.
Regardless of a person's chosen career, if they learn a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future by having life-long skills like these.
Being able to communicate directly with people from a foreign country will put someone who mastered many languages automatically in front of the competition.
According to YouGov's poll of more than 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough for conversation, with French being the language of conversation used by only two-digit percentages, 15 percent.
This is the reason why investing in language education is so important for today's children.
Having multiple languages, especially countries developing their economies, will equip children with better opportunities in finding meaningful jobs.
In Scotland, every school will be different in the language they learn.
Some schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are seen as very important to the UK when looking forward to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child is interested in, there are always plenty of languages to choose from within a private school, with an instructor who specializes in that area.
Scottish private schools are dedicated to providing an atmosphere of learning that will prepare children and provide them with the skills necessary to succeed, whatever the future holds.
There is no denying at this time, in a global business environment, that language continues to be very important to the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern language should be considered an ‘international communication skill.’
Private schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence for young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Private Schools.
