Harvard students have taken courses to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has given all of its students more sleep in an effort to combat the ever-growing culture of learning through a caffeine-based 'overnight'.
An instructor finds students at the world's number one university often can't understand the basics of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and an expert at Brigham and Women's Hospital, provides a course he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He gained inspiration to start the course after giving lectures on the effects of sleep deprivation during learning.
"At the end of the course, a girl came up to me and said: 'Why am I only being told about this now, in my senior year?'
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep - and that surprised me," she told The Telegraph.
This course was introduced for the first time this year, explaining to students the need for good sleep habits to help academic and sporting achievement, as well as improving their well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after finding its students had been sleep-deprived throughout the week.
The one-hour course involves several interactive assignments.
In one section, there is an image of a dormitory room, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, coaches and books to be told about the effects of caffeine and light and how sports performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and the importance of sleep routines.
In the other section, participants were told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
Campus maps with interactive icons, then encourage participants to think about their daily routines.
"We know it's not going to change the behavior of the students right away.
But we believe they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know the health effects when choosing to smoke," added Prof. Czeisler.
A culture of pride in ‘staying up all night' still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing stress on students means sleep deprivation is an increasingly tapering problem.
Making sure you have enough quality sleep, it should be a student's 'secret weapon' to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he says - even to avoid gaining weight, because lack of sleep puts the brain into starvation mode, making it constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student studying chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler plan the course, having taken his class last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to develop the course throughout the campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all postgraduate students to complete the same learning program before joining a competitive institution.
Prof. Czeisler suggests that students should consider the use of alarm clocks before and even after sleep, and be aware of the harmful effects of 'blue light' emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can damage your circadian rhythm from moving, causing sleep problems.
